          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>Single folio on parchment; Shelfmark: EA2009.18.1; Qur'ānic text: Q 21:36-21:42; Dimensions: 395 x 310; Lines per page: 16; Script style: kūfī F.I <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">(See Déroche 1992: pp. 46-47)</ref>; Estimated date of production: 750-900. We only have access to fol. 1 verso at the moment. </p>
              <p>The manuscript EA2009.18.1 has several sister fragments that probably belong to the same codex: </p>
              <p>-Three fragments from the Khalili Collections in London with the shelfmarks <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1052/page/1r?sura=9&amp;amp;verse=92">KFQ 46</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1053/page/1r?sura=6&amp;amp;verse=38">KFQ 47</ref> and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1054/page/1r?sura=3&amp;amp;verse=178">KFQ 71</ref>. See also the catalogue entry by François Déroche about the three fragments (<ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ">The Abbasid Tradition, London 1992, PN: 120</ref>). </p>
              <p>-Five folios from the collection of Los Angeles County Museum of Art with the shelfmarks <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1285/page/1?sura=2&amp;amp;verse=264">M.73.5.508</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1545/page/1r?sura=8&amp;amp;verse=1">M.73.5.510</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1251/page/1r?sura=5&amp;amp;verse=56#manuscript_page">M.73.5.511</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1282/page/1v?sura=7&amp;amp;verse=189">M.73.5.515</ref> and <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1284/page/1r?sura=20&amp;amp;verse=18#manuscript_page">M.2002.1.383</ref>. </p>
              <p>-One folio from the Brooklin Museum with the shelfmark <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1293/page/1v?sura=21&amp;amp;verse=25">1995.186</ref>. </p>
              <p>-One folio from the Seattle Art Museum, shelfmark <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1656/page/1r?sura=5&amp;amp;verse=64">47.100</ref>. </p>
              <p>-One folio from the Dallas Museum of Art, shelfmark <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/1908/page/1r?sura=12&amp;amp;verse=109">K.1.2014.792</ref>. </p>
              <p>-and one folio from the Wereldmuseum, shelfmark <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/3057/page/1r?sura=16&amp;amp;verse=61">TM-4321-2</ref>. </p>
              <p/>
              <p>Gotthelf Bergsträßer Archives contain images of an almost complete codex preserved in the collection of Topkapi Sarayi in Istanbul in this script style, mentioned in <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ">Déroche's catalogue entry (Déroche 1992, PN: 120)</ref>, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/verse-navigator/sura/2/verse/12/manuscripts/54/page/1r">Istanbul: Topkapı Sarayı, 50386" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives)</ref>. Although the script and other features such as text division and ornamentation are very close, EA2009.18.1 is from a different codex because the Istanbul manuscript<ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/manuscripts/54/page/192r?sura=9&amp;amp;verse=92"> 50386</ref> contains the Qurʾānic text of the Ashmolean fragment. </p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>See the website of the institution: <ref target="https://collections.ashmolean.org/object/724621">https://collections.ashmolean.org/object/724621</ref></p>
              <p/>
            </summary>
